Why WAL Data is Not Encrypted - And How to Secure It

The Speed vs Security Tradeoff

WAL prioritizes recovery speed over encryption for three main reasons:

Reason	            Impact	                                    Example
Performance	        Encryption adds 20-30% write latency	    1000 writes/sec becomes 700 writes/sec
Recovery Urgency	Faster crash recovery is more important	    Emergency database restore needs speed
Default Trust	    Assumes secure environment	                Like not encrypting RAM

Real benefit: Keeping WAL unencrypted means your database recovers faster and handles more writes per second.

What WAL Files Actually Contain - The Risk

In etcd WAL files, you can find sensitive data:

Kubernetes secrets (base64 encoded)
Pod specifications
Container images
Pod IP addresses

Real risk: If someone gains access to the control plane node, they can dump WAL files and extract secrets.

Proper Security Approaches for WAL

1. Filesystem Encryption - Best Practice
Encrypt the entire disk partition where etcd stores data.
Example tools: Linux LUKS, Windows BitLocker

Steps: Create encrypted partition, open it, format, then mount at /var/lib/etcd

2. Network Encryption
Configure etcd with TLS for all peer communication.
Settings needed: cert-file, key-file, client-cert-auth enabled

3. Kubernetes-Specific Protections
Use PodSecurityPolicy to restrict etcd pods:
No privilege escalation
Read-only root filesystem
Use secrets for certificates

Real-World Attack Scenario

Without Protection:

Attacker gains access to control plane node
Runs command to dump WAL files and grep for secrets
Extracts all Kubernetes secrets easily

With Protection:

Attacker sees encrypted files
Cannot read any data without decryption key
LUKS encrypted file shown as binary garbage
